    <section class="faq-section" style="margin-top: 4rem;">
        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

        <details>
            <summary>What defines a 'growth' ETF?</summary>
            <p style="margin-top: 0.5rem;">A growth ETF invests in companies expected to grow their earnings and revenue faster than the broader market. These companies typically reinvest profits into expansion rather than paying significant dividends.</p>
        </details>

        <details>
            <summary>Why are expense ratios important for growth ETFs?</summary>
            <p style="margin-top: 0.5rem;">Because growth investing is typically a long-term strategy, even small differences in expense ratios can compound over time, significantly impacting total returns. Lower fees are generally preferable.</p>
        </details>

        <details>
            <summary>How do growth ETFs perform during economic downturns?</summary>
            <p style="margin-top: 0.5rem;">Growth ETFs are often more volatile and may underperform value or dividend ETFs during economic downturns or periods of rising interest rates, as their valuations are heavily based on future expected earnings.</p>
        </details>

        <details>
            <summary>What is the difference between a broad growth ETF and a sector-specific growth ETF?</summary>
            <p style="margin-top: 0.5rem;">A broad growth ETF invests in fast-growing companies across all sectors (e.g., tech, healthcare, consumer). A sector-specific ETF limits its investments to just one industry, offering higher potential reward but greater concentrated risk.</p>
        </details>

        <details>
            <summary>Should I invest in both growth and value ETFs?</summary>
            <p style="margin-top: 0.5rem;">Yes, combining growth and value ETFs can create a balanced 'core' portfolio, allowing investors to capture upside momentum while maintaining stability during market rotations.</p>
        </details>

    </section>
